Please don't go to the Fox Village. There are many photos of these cute foxes online so unfortunately many people add it to their list, but as a travel consultant I have to keep crushing people's dreams when it comes to this. Foxes are not treated great in the Fox village.  People draw the line in different places when it comes to morality but I think that if you have to ask whether a place treats animals well or not, then itâ€™s not a place one should want to visit. A â€œgrey areaâ€ isnâ€™t on the good side when it comes to animal rights.  Obviously they donâ€™t like being touched by people, and so they shouldnâ€™t be (some are chained to the wall so they can't run away when people approach and others are put in "petting cages"). Foxes are not pack animals either and there shouldnâ€™t be so many living together in one place either, thatâ€™s not how they live in the wild. They often fight among themselves and are almost obligated to fight for food that is thrown at them, many times this results in injuries.  Many of them are also in tiny cages. People like to point out that the foxes in cages are pregnant or sick (though not all), however thatâ€™s still no excuse to trap them in such tiny spaces. If it's true that the foxes are put in cages when pregnant, that's two months that they will be locked up there.  I wouldnâ€™t go if you like animals. Beyond cute furry animals photos, here you can see "the other side" of the fox village:  Reviews: https://www.tripadvisor.ie/Attraction_Review-g1023408-d7388189-Reviews-Miyagi_Zao_Fox_Village-Shiroishi_Miyagi_Prefecture_Tohoku.html  Photos: https://preview.ibb.co/juQamQ/Screen_Shot_2017_05_08_at_21_26_19.png  Also, while we're on the topic of animal rights, note that Miyajima island also has a ban against feeding deer. This would seem fine in another situation, but these deer have been fed for centuries before and this law is newer. The deer are tame and are not able to hunt or look for food on their own, resulting in many of the island's deer being very underfed and sickly-looking. If you like deer, I'd recommend Nara instead.  The mentioned Okunoshima, the rabbit island, and Jigokudani, the monkey onsen, are good places to visit if you want to see animals, as both live in liberty and are treated well.

Just FYI, all 3 writing systems are definitely needed in Japanese: Hiragana, Katakana, and Kanji. I wouldn't necessarily say that they act as "word dividers" (@9:30)  because some words are conjugated verbs that require both kanji and hiragana, e.g. è¡Œãã¾ã™ = I'm going/I will go. It would be awkward to think that the kanji character isn't "attached" to the hiragana in this case because if they were read as two separate entities, or "word dividers," it wouldn't make sense. Once you begin to learn Japanese, hiragana is used not only for vocabulary words, but for grammar as well. Just some constructive criticism. :)

Fun Fact about Seven-Eleven  Seven-Eleven was founded in Oak Cliff Texas in 1927 as an ice retail store. After a while, they expanded their business and sold other daily goods. In 1971 most of their shops became open 24h a day. In 1974 they opened their first shop in Japan, also they made Seven-Eleven Japan at this point. It was a mega-hit in Japan, but due to some problems that they encountered, they changed their business into a franchise-styled one. In 1991 Seven-Eleven Japan bought Seven-Eleven (the original one in the USA).   So technically Seven-Eleven was founded in America and grew in Japan.

You forgot to mention the climate and especially the snow. While the biggest cities like Tokyo or Osaka barely get any snow, Japan is still home to some of the snowiest cities in the world. In fact the three snowiest cities in the world (Aomori, Sapporo, Toyama) are all located in Japan. Then, there's also a lot of other cities, some even smaller, that still get a lot of snow like Akita, Yamagata, Hakodate, Hirosaki, Otaru, Asahikawa, Sakata, Joetsu, Tottori, Wakkanai, Niigata, Kanazawa and Fukui. Some of these even get more snow than the ones on the official list of the top 10 snowiest cities but they're too small to be represented. The cities of Matsue and Sendai also get a relatively good amount of snow every year. Probably just a little more than New York does. Then, of course, there's the Monsoon season, where some places (especially in the North) get just over 100 mm of rain in September, whereas in Kochi prefecture (Shikoku) some places even get over 400 mm of rain in September. September is generally the rainiest month in Japan, although it depends. In some other parts, it's July and in Kanazawa it's even December due to the Siberian winds and the sea of Japan

Masao Son(Soft Bank, Yahoo Japan) was ethnic Korean, born in Fukuoka Japan, 3rd generation Korean in Japan. He kept his nationality as South Korean before he naturalized as Japanese about 30yrs ago for the request from Japanese government, after his success in business. For the proposal, he made a condition to the government that his family name should be remained and registered as it is. But the Japanese government didn't allowed his condition by the reason that there was no such family name in Japan at the time. Koreans should change his family name as Japanese style at the time(Now abolished). So his wife, who is Japanese, created 'Son' as a Japanese family name(Japanese could create new family name), then he applied Son as his Japanese family name following his wife. It is well known story both in Japan and Korea. His family name Son is as same as the English primier soccer player Heung-min Son.

I practice Shinto. It's not actually as unique as is posited here. Its simply a local form of Animism with ancestor and nature worship. Animism is the belief that "spirit" or whatever you wish to call it (essence, chi, maori, what have you) inhabits everything. Trees, rocks, rivers, even tools and weapons. Rituals are about honouring one's ancestors and connecting with the forces of nature and keeping them in balance.   It's identical to all ancient beliefs (native american, african, siberian, chinese, polynesian, irish etc.) that are diverse only for its cultural variety, but the belief system is the same.  Also, it's not escapist, because the belief is that the world of kami, or the spirit world, intertwines with our own world. The idea that it's an escape is a western construct, where the world of "faerie tales" (faeries and mermaids, who are kami of forests and waters) is supposed to be imaginary. Not so in animism: that world is seen as real and present.

The Sea of Japan (or the Japan Sea) is a sea area located along the northeastern part of the Asian continent. It is separated from the North Pacific Ocean by the Japanese Archipelago and Sakhalin.  Historically, the nameâ€œSea of Japanâ€ was first established in Europe from the late 18th century to the early 19th century,and has been used for more than 200 years. When seas are separated from oceans, they have been frequently named after major archipelagos or peninsulas that separate them. The nameâ€œSea of Japan" focuses on one key geographical feature - the Japanese Archipelago that separates this sea area from the Northern Pacific Ocean.  In fact, without the presence of the Japanese Archipelago, this sea area would not exist.  Because of this obvious geographical characteristic, the name â€œSea of Japanâ€ came to be widely accepted throughout the world. At present, more than 97% of the maps used around the world, except for those in the Republic of Korea (ROK) and North Korea, use only the name â€œSea of Japan". This name has been internationally established.  Despite this global recognition, ROK and North Korea suddenly proposed that the name â€œSea of Japanâ€ should be changed at the sixth United Nations Conference on the Standardization of Geographical Names in 1992. They continue to raise this issue at related international conferences of the United Nations and at meetings of the International Hydrographic Organization (IHO).  They argue that the name â€œSea of Japanâ€ became widely used from the beginning of the 20th century, as a result of Japan's expansionism and colonialism. For this reason, they maintain that the name should be changed to the â€œEast Sea," as ROK and North Korea domestically use,or at least, that both the â€œEast Seaâ€ and the â€œSea of Japanâ€ should be used together. However, the assertion made by ROK and North Korea is unfounded, and there is neither reasoning nor merit behind the call for such a change.

The Sea of Japan (or the Japan Sea) is a sea area located along the northeastern part of the Asian continent. It is separated from the North Pacific Ocean by the Japanese Archipelago and Sakhalin.  Historically, the nameâ€œSea of Japanâ€ was first established in Europe from the late 18th century to the early 19th century,and has been used for more than 200 years. When seas are separated from oceans, they have been frequently named after major archipelagos or peninsulas that separate them. The nameâ€œSea of Japan" focuses on one key geographical feature - the Japanese Archipelago that separates this sea area from the Northern Pacific Ocean.  In fact, without the presence of the Japanese Archipelago, this sea area would not exist.  Because of this obvious geographical characteristic, the name â€œSea of Japanâ€ came to be widely accepted throughout the world. At present, more than 97% of the maps used around the world, except for those in the Republic of Korea (ROK) and North Korea, use only the name â€œSea of Japan". This name has been internationally established.  Despite this global recognition, ROK and North Korea suddenly proposed that the name â€œSea of Japanâ€ should be changed at the sixth United Nations Conference on the Standardization of Geographical Names in 1992. They continue to raise this issue at related international conferences of the United Nations and at meetings of the International Hydrographic Organization (IHO).  They argue that the name â€œSea of Japanâ€ became widely used from the beginning of the 20th century, as a result of Japan's expansionism and colonialism. For this reason, they maintain that the name should be changed to the â€œEast Sea," as ROK and North Korea domestically use,or at least, that both the â€œEast Seaâ€ and the â€œSea of Japanâ€ should be used together. However, the assertion made by ROK and North Korea is unfounded, and there is neither reasoning nor merit behind the call for such a change.

You missed out Japan being close friends and doing a lot of business with Indonesia. They have a pretty strong bond, considering their past. Also Scotland as well, as Japan and Scotland have been close for a long time. Japanese Tourist attribute to a massive chunk of the annually tourist revenue in Scotland, they also have a fondness for Scottish knitted clothing within Japan itself as we export a lot of it, Fond lovers of Whiskey and had a large export quota and had a deep connection over the brewing of their own Whiskey and I think it was the owner of Yamasaki lived in Scotland for a while to learn from a brew-master on how to make Scotch and now they export a lot of the raw materials so they can make their own and they are one of the many nations that keep the process as a close to the traditional Scottish way as possible as nod to the brew-masters. It was Scotland that was commissioned by Japan to build all the coastal lighthouses in the 1800's. Aside from that we have had a pretty long and friendly history. Our National Museum has honoured Japanese history by having a space dedicated to educating those about this amazing history and culture and also in Japan within Tokyo they have honoured Scotland by having a "Scotland day" within one of their museum or galleries celebrating Scottish history.  We used to get quite a lot of Japanese teenagers travelling around Scottish schools  for cultural exchange as well. It's the reason why I've been amazed and in love with Japan since I was 8 years old. Even that young being taught about the country and meeting Japanese natives was great.  When I hit my early 20's I eventually had enough money to visit and was not disappointed. Need to return and travel around more, it's a dream of mine.

When Japanese invaded the Ryukyu Kingdom and subjected it, they issued decrees to ban any weapons to stop potential rebellions. Bangladeshâ€™s national flag was established from the model of the Japanese flag of the Rising Sun. The red circle on the flag expresses the sun that rises, while the green conveys the rich earth. Moreover, the red symbolizes the blood of those killed in the war of independence.  When Professor Nagoshi Futaranosuke, formerly of Takachiho University, asked about the origin of the Bangladesh national flag to Japanese Embassy in Bangladesh, the public relations official said, â€œYearning for Japan.â€  Bangladesh means â€œthe country of Bengalâ€. Three Bengalis who pride themselves in their close ties with Japan are: Tagore, a poet who won the Nobel Prize for Asian literature; Chandra Bose, who risked his life for the independence of India; and Radhabinod Pal, a judge. Tagore was a friend of Tenshin Okakura. He visited Japan several times. Because of Chandra Bose, the Japanese supported the independence of India. Pal asserted that the Japanese were not guilty in the Japanese war crimes trial.

Well according to you I am criminally insane, since I started to learn Japanese and well I am actually understanding it. I am at a beginner level but that is only in 5 days, I bought a book that is for complete beginners and I have been doing 1 lesson every day, and I my reading comprehension and understanding of Japanese has increased steadily, Grammar, how to write hiragana so far, vocabulary. I still don't know enough where I could speak it in any way fluidly or even write anything like what I am writing but well now Hiragana is no longer just a bunch of weird letters to me, but rather I can read it now, I can write and think of responses for specific things I have seen so far, like age, question of what is, who is, whose is it, simple descriptions, colours,some basic vocabulary that comes in the lessons so far, how to introduce one self, greetings and farewells, numbers, how to say if I like or dislike something, how to ask if someone likes or dislikes something. I am currently in the fifth lesson of 13 of the first of 4 books, I am planning on going through all of them as fast as possible, trying to continue my 1 lesson per day goal, hopefully eventually getting a good enough mastery of Japanese and the written language so I can start reading texts and consume media in Japanese as a way to reinforce the language skills I am acquiring, and avoid what happened with my french where I can barely even string together a sentence anymore.

This feels a bit outdated because the reality of Japan now is that pretty much everything there, including the transportation is aging. Very badly as a matter of fact. The country is in a serious denial about its own empirial downfall and its effects become apparent after visiting other Asian powerhouses like China and South Korea or even aforementioned Taiwan.    Japan WAS all this a decade ago, but since early 2000s has been in a constant freefall with the economy/population/innovation being completely overtaken by neighbors and Japan living in the illusion of past glories.   The Japanese transportation for example pales in comparison to its neighbor South Korea or the new developments in China. Its monetary system and financial transactions are also very outdated. Yes credit cards (and even bitcoin) is accepted in certain places, but I can literally pay for everything through a QR code or an NFC chip in both China and Korea. I don't even need a credit card anymore or suffer horrible transaction fees. The work culture and the education has been on a steady decline as well, with most Japanese universities consistently losing ranking to its neighbors. I could go on...but the idea is that... Similarly to how other conservative societies died out because of their inability to adapt and change, Japan in 20-30 years will most likely become just a minor power with glorious past.

Small nitpick - Tokyo, Kyoto, and Osaka prefectures aren't each a single city. All three of them contain multiple cities, towns, and villages. Kyoto-fu, for example, contains 15 cities, 6 towns, and 1 village. Tokyo-to contains 23 wards (collectively "Tokyo city"), 26 other cities, 5 towns, and 8 villages. An interesting geographical footnote is that 9 of these towns and villages in Tokyo-to are actually on remote islands, some of them hundreds of miles away from Honshu.

I really enjoyed the video, but I feel obligated to point out that you incorrectly said Tokugawa Leyasu. It is actually Ieyasu with an i and not an L. I'm assuming this was just a minor mistake caused by the fact that capital i looks like lower-case L. The Japanese language actually doesn't have the letter L, which is why they use R to create a similar sound for borrowed / foreign words (hence why jokes about the Japanese accent always has L's exchanged with R's).

I read a book about the evolution of languages and they mentioned a scale that's used to rank how difficult it is to learn one language vs another (like French to English/English to French). the scale was 0 to 5, 0 being a local dialect such as American English to British English, 1 being a more regional dialect with a thick accent or alot of specific slang like American to Cockney, 2 was a mutually intelligible language where alot of the words are very similar like some of the Scandinavian languages or the Romance language (Spanish and Italian and French), 3 were language outside of the same language family like English to Russian, and 4 were languages that werent even remotely close like English to Swahili. Chinese, Korean, and Japanese were a few of the only level 5 languages due to incomprehensible alphabets, alien syntax, and the languages being almost completely unrelated to any other languages on earth. On average they said it took about 5 times as long (measured in hours of study and practice) to go from most Western languages to Japanese as it did to go from a language like French to English. Even going from some languages like English to Thai or Vietnamese took much less time then Japanese, Korean, and Chinese.

Overall: good video. Minor error:  Your said, "Most students have to learn about 2000-3000 of these."  However, it is nowhere close to 3000.  Students in Japan learn Joyo Kanji (everyday-use kanji) which is 2,136 as of year 2010.  I know from my own study and experience (because I live in Japan) that not many Japanese people know more than 2000.    Some words which may have a more difficult kanji might be written in just hiragana without kanji, or written with kanji plus the furigana pronunciation along side the kanji.  For example, hiragana can be written with kanji (å¹³ä»®å) but most people I know write it without kanji (ã²ã‚‰ãŒãª).  And yes, I agree that many Chinese people can understand or guess the meaning of Japanese signs and restaurant menus by looking at the kanji.  I have seen this happen.  Error #2: You said, "A small 3% are Christian."  Most source that I found state Japan is about 1% Christian.  However, many pastors and Christian missionaries will say, "less than 1%."  In any case, it's a small minority.  Christmas Day is a regular work day, not a holiday in Japan.

12:54  You don't call Emperor Hirohito "Emperor Hirohito".  The years in which the Emperor rules is designated with an Era name, and when the Emperor dies the Japanese only refer to him by this Era name, which was ShÅwa, so he is now called Emperor ShÅwa.  When he was alive they never referred to him by his given name but called him "His Majesty the Emperor" or "His Majesty".  Compare, "The Knights Who Until Recently Said 'Nee!'"  The Japanese have a system of honorifics which totally modified the verbs depending on who you were speaking to, and you used the tip-top honorifics when speaking to an Emperor, which are forms of speech the young Japanese have probably forgotten entirely.  Emperor Akihito is the current emperor, and his Era has been named Heisei, so he will be Emperor Heisei upon death.

Japan was minding its own business.   It was forced open by Western powers.  They looked around the world and saw colonization and domination by the west.  Africa was cut up. Colonies were still all around the world. China was subject to unequal treaties. And the Westerners were now interfering with Japanese affairs... indirectly culminating in the overthrow of the +250 year old government.   Unable to directly get the foreigners out of their affairs through their antiquated military, the new government played a long game that would focus on rapid modernization in order to make a Japan strong enough to gain independence from the foreigners. Included in this was the eventual annexation of Korea and Machuria for resources and as a geographic buffer from China and Russia.  They gained a lot of the new territory using similar sorts of slimy methods that the West had used. And they treated the people they annexed horribly. No ethics, and likely fueled by racism and nationalism- there's no excuse.  But the basic point- protect Japan from the land-grabbing and meddling West, even if that meant undertaking their own landgrabbing and meddling, was quite logical.  Now that most borders and such are pretty much settled, this may seem drastic. But they weren't back then.  The US had just mugged Mexico for California and what is now the SW USA in 1848, about 15 years earlier.  European borders were by no means set, especially in areas like Poland and Ukraine that served as a buffer zone between Russian and the rest of Europe. Countries were constantly at war for territory, and if you didn't want someone to take your land, you needed to be able to protect it.  Kyuushuu is closer to Korea than it is to Tokyo. It is more or less indefensible to an invasion through Korea. So yes, the threat was real, and they did what they thought they had to to survive in a world full of wolves.

Japan didn't close until sometime in the 1600s.  Westerners didn't even get to Japan until sometime in the 1500s. The Portuguese were the first, but this was the stage of history when proselytizing was as much if not more a political power play than actually about religion. And since this was a power consolidation stage of Japanese history after a long period of upheaval, that sort of foreign influence was deemed harmful and they were largely removed. Tempura, and probably a bunch of other things, has Portuguese roots though.  Even when they were closed, they still traded with Asia, and had one Dutch port in Nagasaki.  Japan was forced open again in the mid 1800s... ~80 years before WWII. Westerners immediately began meddling in Japanese affairs, and in short order, the shogunate which had reigned over the closed period was removed and the emperor brought back to power. Having been forced open and meddled with, and having seen the global colonization by the West- and where colonization was impossible, unequal trade treaties... Japan underwent rapid modernization so as to protect itself... which eventually led to something along the lines of a better to join the bullies than be bullied sort of thought process that fed the ultra-nationalism that led to the Asian wars up to and including WWII.

Japan is like a mix between Germany, England and France. It is an island nation, where people drive on the left side of the road, and people are overly polite, and they have a royal family, very much like England. But Japan is also very industrious, excelling in engineering and manufacturing, much like the Germans. Big automotive and electronic industries such as Honda, Toyota, Nissan and Hitachi competing with Volkswagen, BMW, Mercedes Benz and Siemens. The Japanese are very much career oriented like the Germans, (though they work hell lot longer, and are probably a little less efficient), and have a very serious outlook in life (why else is the suicide rate so high). Their culture is also one that is promotes artistic balance like the French, as seen through their appreciation of good food, traditional architecture and landscaping, modern infrastructure, and traditional and modern fashion. Food such as sushi is served in gourmet style that is aesthetically simple and pleasing, but also very hard to master, requiring particular skills and training very much like French recipes. Japan is also the country with the most number of Michelin 3-Star restaurants. Among Asia, it is a leader in fashion, with designers such as Rei Kawakubo, Yohji Yamamoto, Junya Watanabe, and Kenzo Takada having found success as couturiers in Paris Fashion Week.

+sion8 Rhenium is an extremely rare refractory metal, primarily used for rocket and fighter jet engines. It was the last element with any stable isotopes discovered, and it usually has to be extracted from other deposits as a trace element, which is an extremely expensive and time-consuming process.  That's why actually having a steady source of Rhenium Sulfide is such a strategic asset, even if it's in the middle of a volcano or only produces 20-60kg a year.

According to the internet, Hafnium was the last stable element to be discovered, and since there appears to be only the one stable isotope of rhenium...  I also don't buy that that's at all why Rhenium would be valuable to Russia. Maybe if they don't have another source, but 20-60 kg a year is negligible compared to the 40-50 tonnes of Rhenium extracted a year.

Whoops, it was second to last after all. thanks for catching that.  Also I think the reason why this 20-60kg/year is so significant is that 1) it's in a very concentrated disulfide form, so there's less refining and processing to be done, and 2) the find is located in Russian territory; according to Wikipedia the largest producers of Rhenium are Chile, the US, Peru and Poland, none of which are sufficiently friendly towards Russia to traffic in a highly strategic resource like this.  At least, that's how I see it.

I enjoy your videos, but man, this one is bad.  Badly worded and misleading bits all over the place. Way too many pictures of "weird" things and very few representative pictures of food, scenery, etc.  Bad explanations of the things you do choose to talk about: the reasons for the demographic decline (how about non-existence of work-life balance, 25+ years of economic stagnation, and the high cost of raising children?), escapism caused by "diplomatic isolation" (where did you even get this from??).  Then there's the writing section. Yikes. First, they're "scripts", not "alphabets. More importantly, instead of stating in 5 seconds, "Roughly, Kanji are used for ordinary word roots, hiragana for grammatical words and suffixes, and katakana for loan words and technical terms", you ramble about word boundaries and make it sound like this is relevant to whether the system could be scrapped (it isn't).  On top of this there's the photo error others noted, misspelling and mispronouncing "Ieyasu" as "Leyasu", and simple factual errors (7-Eleven did not start in Japan).  What happened? It sounds like you usually gather information from natives of the country in question, but this time it looks like you barely did any research and didn't bother running the script by one knowledgeable person. (Or are they usually this bad and I just haven't noticed?)

He was forced to exile himself and most of his followers to Manila, and the Spanish colonial government in Manila even offered him to invade Japan and overthrow the Shogunate to protect Japanese Christians; he refused and opposed to this. He died 40 days after his arrival in Manila, and was buried with full military honors as a daimyo, making him the only daimyo buried in Philippine soil. Also, the barangay (urban district) of Mintal in Davao City is known as the "Little Tokyo" of the Philippines. Please don't go to the Fox Village. There are many photos of these cute foxes online so unfortunately many people add it to their list, but as a travel consultant I have to keep crushing people's dreams when it comes to this. Foxes are not treated great in the Fox village.  People draw the line in different places when it comes to morality but I think that if you have to ask whether a place treats animals well or not, then itâ€™s not a place one should want to visit. A â€œgrey areaâ€ isnâ€™t on the good side when it comes to animal rights.  Obviously they donâ€™t like being touched by people, and so they shouldnâ€™t be (some are chained to the wall so they can't run away when people approach and others are put in "petting cages"). Foxes are not pack animals either and there shouldnâ€™t be so many living together in one place either, thatâ€™s not how they live in the wild. They often fight among themselves and are almost obligated to fight for food that is thrown at them, many times this results in injuries.  Many of them are also in tiny cages. People like to point out that the foxes in cages are pregnant or sick (though not all), however thatâ€™s still no excuse to trap them in such tiny spaces. If it's true that the foxes are put in cages when pregnant, that's two months that they will be locked up there.  I wouldnâ€™t go if you like animals. Beyond cute furry animals photos, here you can see "the other side" of the fox village:  Photos: https://preview.ibb.co/juQamQ/Screen_Shot_2017_05_08_at_21_26_19.png  Also, while we're on the topic of animal rights, note that Miyajima island also has a ban against feeding deer. This would seem fine in another situation, but these deer have been fed for centuries before and this law is newer. The deer are tame and are not able to hunt or look for food on their own, resulting in many of the island's deer being very underfed and sickly-looking. If you like deer, I'd recommend Nara instead.  Okunoshima, the rabbit island, and Jigokudani, the monkey onsens, are good places to visit if you want to see animals, as both live in liberty and are treated well.

Please don't go to the Fox Village. There are many photos of these cute foxes online so unfortunately many people add it to their list, but as a travel consultant I have to keep crushing people's dreams when it comes to this. Foxes are not treated great in the Fox village.  People draw the line in different places when it comes to morality but I think that if you have to ask whether a place treats animals well or not, then itâ€™s not a place one should want to visit. A â€œgrey areaâ€ isnâ€™t on the good side when it comes to animal rights.  Obviously they donâ€™t like being touched by people, and so they shouldnâ€™t be (some are chained to the wall so they can't run away when people approach and others are put in "petting cages"). Foxes are not pack animals either and there shouldnâ€™t be so many living together in one place either, thatâ€™s not how they live in the wild. They often fight among themselves and are almost obligated to fight for food that is thrown at them, many times this results in injuries.  Many of them are also in tiny cages. People like to point out that the foxes in cages are pregnant or sick (though not all), however thatâ€™s still no excuse to trap them in such tiny spaces. If it's true that the foxes are put in cages when pregnant, that's two months that they will be locked up there.  I wouldnâ€™t go if you like animals. Beyond cute furry animals photos, here you can see "the other side" of the fox village:  Reviews: https://www.tripadvisor.ie/Attraction_Review-g1023408-d7388189-Reviews-Miyagi_Zao_Fox_Village-Shiroishi_Miyagi_Prefecture_Tohoku.html  Photos: https://preview.ibb.co/juQamQ/Screen_Shot_2017_05_08_at_21_26_19.png  Also, while we're on the topic of animal rights, note that Miyajima island also has a ban against feeding deer. This would seem fine in another situation, but these deer have been fed for centuries before and this law is newer. The deer are tame and are not able to hunt or look for food on their own, resulting in many of the island's deer being very underfed and sickly-looking. If you like deer, I'd recommend Nara instead.  The mentioned Okunoshima, the rabbit island, and Jigokudani, the monkey onsen, are good places to visit if you want to see animals, as both live in liberty and are treated well.

Just FYI, all 3 writing systems are definitely needed in Japanese: Hiragana, Katakana, and Kanji. It would be awkward to think that the kanji character isn't "attached" to the hiragana in this case because if they were read as two separate entities, or "word dividers," it wouldn't make sense.
